    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1932-05-10T13:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1932-05-10T13:00:00-05:00" n="78"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d78">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">500.A15A4/1022: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in Great Britain (<persName corresp="#p_MAW1"
                            type="from">Mellon</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Acting Secretary
                            of State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">London</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1932-05-10T19:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 10, 1932—7 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received May 10—2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>167. From <persName corresp="#p_GHS1">Gibson</persName>. Embassy’s telegram 166,
                    May 10, 6 p.m. This afternoon I had a conversation with <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM1">Malcolm MacDonald</persName> in order that the Prime
                    Minister might be informed as to the purpose of our visit in conformity with the
                    Secretary’s instructions. He said that he would have an opportunity to talk to
                    his father tomorrow, would tell him of our conversations thus far and let me
                    know if there was anything the Prime Minister had to suggest. <persName
                        corresp="#p_MM1">Malcolm MacDonald</persName> said [he] was sufficiently
                    familiar with his father’s views on this subject to feel sure he would be in
                    favor of pressing the conversations forward as soon as some responsible French
                    representative could participate. It does not now seem probable that the Prime
                    Minister will be in a position to deal with disarmament questions until after
                    the Lausanne Conference<note n="2" xml:id="d78fn2">See <ref target="#pg_636">pp.
                            636</ref> ff.</note> so that arrangements would have to be made for
                    someone else to represent this country.</p>
                <p>Please repeat to the Secretary. [<persName corresp="#p_GHS1"
                    >Gibson</persName>.]</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_MAW1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Mellon</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
